Paperback books appear to have a positive trend with no seasonality. Seasonality does not exist because there is not a consistent pattern in relation to time. Instead, it is more random. Visually, we can possibly also rule out a multiplicative model because the amplitudes do not continue to widen and there is not an exponential growth. Since the previous exercise used an additive and damped Holt model (A, Ad, N), this will most likely be the best method. According to the ETS Table, the model’s components are:

  • \(y_t = l_{t-1} + {\phi}b_{t-1} + {\epsilon}_t\)
  • \(l_t = l_{t-1} + {\phi}b_{t-1} + {\alpha}{\epsilon}_t\)
  • \(b_t = {\phi}b_{t-1} + {\beta}{\epsilon}_t\)

When comparing models, the analyst should try to achieve the lowest AIC, AICc, and RMSE. In terms of forecasting, a minimum value for the Akaike’s Information Criterion is best. Additionally, the following smoothing parameters are:

  • \(\alpha\): The estimated smoothing coefficient is 0.03259223. As the value is closer to 0, this means that more weight is given to observations from the more distant past.

  • \(\beta\): The estimated smoothing coefficient for the slope is 0.0001000242. This means that the slope does not change often even if there are slight changes.

  • \(\phi\): The \(\phi\) represents the dampened effect. The value is 0.98, which suggests that the damped model is not able to be distinguished from a non-damped model.

To ensure that this is the optimal choice, we run model() to see what method is produced. It suggests using an additive SES model (A, N, N), but this is problematic since we have already identified that there is a trend. Even though this model has a better AIC, intuitively, we will stick with the first model presented, Holt’s (A, Ad, N).

1.1 Forecast Sales

The graph shows a 10-day forecast for paperback book sales. Within the shaded portion to the right, the reader will see smoothed prediction intervals for this specific time period. These PIs give an interval within which \(y_t\) is expected to lie within a certain probability. Typically, the 80% and 95% intervals are used. This statistical tool is helpful because it expresses the uncertainty in the forecast. It is much clearer how much is unknown with the associated forecast. In addition, the variance appears to be increasing with time.

Prediction interval: \(\hat{y}_{T+h|T}{\pm}{c}\hat{\sigma}_h\)

  • Level equation: \(l_t = {\alpha}y_t + (1 - {\alpha})(l_{t-1} +b_{t-1})\). This shows that \(l_t\) is a weighted average of observation and the one-step-ahead training forecast for time \(t\).

  • Trend equation: This shows that \(b_t\) is a weighted average of the estimated trend at time \(t\) based on \(l_t - l_{t-1}\) and \(b_{t-1}\), the previous estimate of the trend. For this model, the slope is trending downward due to the damped effect.

  • Remainder component: Containing what is not included in the time series. It appears to be random and show no pattern.

1.2 Residuals

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  fitted_values$.resid
## W = 0.97847, p-value = 0.7835

Although checking residuals is not essential for forecasting, it makes calculating the prediction intervals much easier. Therefore, they should be checked to see if they are normally distributed. By using the gg_tsresiduals() function, it is seen that the errors do look slightly skewed. In addition, the correlogram shows that at lag 3 exceeds the dashed blue lines which indicate whether the correlations are significantly different from zero.

The QQ Plot of residuals appears to be possibly non-normal due to the points not being on the line. To determine if the residuals are normally distributed, we run a Shapiro-Walk test. The null hypothesis is that the errors are normally distributed. Since the p-value is greater than \(\alpha\) at 0.05, there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. The residuals can be assumed to be normally distributed.

1.3 Bootstapping Method

According to Chapter 5.5, ‘When a normal distribution for the residuals is an unreasonable assumption, one alternative is to use bootstrapping, which only assumes that the residuals are uncorrelated with constant variance.’ Therefore, we release the assumption of normality and bootstrap instead of simulate.

The method of bootstrapping is used for a time series in order to simulate future values of a series using a model by the residuals. Sometimes, this is used because the normal distribution does not fit to the errors. The idea is to draw at random the new error from the sample of estimated errors with replacement. Instead of simulating with normality, we simulate a random sample of independent errors from the set with equal probability. Since there are many samples, this gives the bookstore owner the opportunity to make informed decisions about different sales situations and take action. By applying this method, it can help them quantify uncertainty in the near future to combat any potential challenges from the historical data that was previously collected. Additionally, bootstrapping would allow the owner to know the prediction intervals which are based on a normal distribution.

The prediction intervals at 95% for the 10-days ahead are between a minimum of 142.37 and a maximum 269.06. Each day, the prediction intervals typically widen until the tenth forecast. The distribution for the next five days seems normally distributed as the mean and median are within one unit of each other (mean: 1032.1, median: 1031.1). The estimated probability that sales will increase in the next 3 days is 17.0%. The chances that sales goes down is lower at 13.7%. Depending on the seed number, these values can differ from other analyses.
